wiki.content: "Yikes" is a confident and bold anthem that celebrates self-reliance and addresses her critics. The lyrics convey a sense of power and superiority, with Nicki asserting her status as the queen of the rap game. In the first verse, she dismisses those who try to undermine her, proclaiming that she is capable of cutting off anyone who disrespects her. The mention of a "Makk truck, not a black truck" suggests that she is a force to be reckoned with and won't hesitate to take action. She also references Rosa Parks, suggesting that she is unafraid to stand up for herself and challenge societal norms. The chorus reinforces her dominance by stating that she plays the game of life on her terms. She sees those who seek attention and validation (clowns who do it for "likes") as beneath her. The line "this is something light" implies that the challenges she faces are insignificant compared to her strength. In the second verse, Nicki highlights her material success and attractiveness, boasting about her expensive Fendi designs and her ability to attract beautiful women. She rejects negative energy and evil influences, emphasizing that she only surrounds herself with positive vibes. The outro serves as a final statement, declaring that she has little interest in those who talk without backing it up with action. Money speaks louder than words, and she maintains her dominance through her success. Overall, "Yikes" is a fierce anthem of self-assurance, with Nicki Minaj asserting her position as a powerful figure who won't tolerate disrespect or negativity. It is a celebration of her success and status in the industry, as well as a declaration of her unapologetic confidence. Read more on Last.fm.
